nodes.title: Framecount Note
widgets_values: This sets the animation length for Image Mode. Use frame load cap for Vid2Vid.

nodes.title: Source Mode Note
widgets_values:
#1 for Img2Vid (Image Mode)
#2 for Vid2Vid (Video Mode)
Disable colored groups not being used. To save time, disable the "Input Gen & CN" groups to fine-tune your masks before sending them to the KSampler.

The Black mask will stylize everything that isn't masked, and creates the mask for the Source Input Background Mode if chosen. The colored masks are merged together and saved for visual/editing purposes only. Disable their "save output" if you wish. To save VRAM, it's recommended to let the Black mask be the last and most behind element in the scene, like a sky.

Colored masks stack as followed: far (White) to near (Yellow). If creating a custom stack, order the colors accordingly to the distance of scene elements.

This workflow allows you to segment up to 8 different elements from an input image, or video, into colored masks for IPA to stylize and animate each element with.

First, select your source input mode in the middle with the switch. 1 is Image Mode, 2 is Video Mode.

At the top of each colored layer is a GDINO-SAM node and a prompt field to type in which element to isolate from your input. The BLACK layer is your background and anything that isn't masked. The prompt fields are filled with some basic examples, but you can change them into whatever you want related to your input, like objects, landscape stuff, or even colors. 

You can increase the threshold under the prompt to affect how strong it tries to isolate the keyword. Lower threshold is weaker and will mask bleed into other things. Higher threshold will try to tighten the mask, but too high and it won't mask anything. A good spot is around 0.30.

On the "GrowMaskWithBlur" node, you can customize the mask using the expand and blur radius settings.

Colored mask layers not being used should be bypassed with the "Fast Groups Bypasser" node. You can also bypass the "Input Gen & CN" groups so you can fine-tune your masks before going into the KSampler.

There are HRFix upscaling groups as well. HRFix_NNLatent is similar to HRFix, but creates a softer image, and can be turned to the SDXL version for a difference in color and detail. HRFix_Ultrasharp does a model upscale pass on the HRFix output for increased resolution and enhanced details.

The ControlNet weights can be adjusted to control how delineated the IPA stylization is. Lower weight on the CN will give more freedom to the masks and retain less of the Source Input edges, causing mask bleed. Higher CN weight will produce more of the Source Input structure, but less quality on the stylization.

If you use this workflow, please feel free to tag me so I can see your awesome work!

nodes.title: Background Mode Note
widgets_values:
Background Mode sets the black mask to use either IPA for stylization (default), or the Source Input behind all other masks as a background.

#1 - IPA
#2 - Source Input
